## The Core Idea

Every time you use `+` to concatenate strings in Java, Java creates a **brand new String object** in memory. It does not add to the existing one — it throws the old one away and builds a new one from scratch.

This is because Strings in Java are **immutable** — once created, they cannot be changed.

---

## Why That Makes a Loop Expensive

```java
String result = "";
result = result + "a";   // creates new String "a"
result = result + "b";   // throws away "a", creates new String "ab"
result = result + "c";   // throws away "ab", creates new String "abc"
result = result + "d";   // throws away "abc", creates new String "abcd"
```

Each step copies everything from before, then adds one character. So:

```
step 1 → copy 0 chars + add "a"   = 1 operation
step 2 → copy 1 char  + add "b"   = 2 operations
step 3 → copy 2 chars + add "c"   = 3 operations
step 4 → copy 3 chars + add "d"   = 4 operations

total = 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 = 10 operations for 4 characters
```

For n characters that becomes `1 + 2 + 3 + ... + n` which is **O(n²)**.

At small scale you never notice. At 10,000 characters in a loop — your code crawls.

---

## StringBuilder Fixes This

`StringBuilder` is a **mutable** character buffer. It does not create a new object on every append — it writes into the same memory, expanding it only when needed.

```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
sb.append("a");   // writes 'a' into buffer
sb.append("b");   // writes 'b' next to it — no copy
sb.append("c");   // writes 'c' next to it — no copy
sb.append("d");   // writes 'd' next to it — no copy

String result = sb.toString(); // convert to String once at the end
```

Each append is one operation regardless of how long the string already is. That is **O(1) per append**, so the whole loop is **O(n)**.

---

## Side by Side

```java
// WRONG — O(n²) — new String object created every iteration
String result = "";
for (String word : words) {
    result += word;
}

// CORRECT — O(n) — one buffer, one object, append in place
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
for (String word : words) {
    sb.append(word);
}
String result = sb.toString();
```

---

## The Memory Picture

```
String concatenation in a loop:

step 1:  [a]
step 2:  [a][b]          ← "a" copied again + "b" added
step 3:  [a][b][c]       ← "ab" copied again + "c" added
step 4:  [a][b][c][d]    ← "abc" copied again + "d" added

Each step re-copies everything. Old objects become garbage.


StringBuilder:

buffer:  [a]             ← append "a"
buffer:  [a][b]          ← append "b" in place
buffer:  [a][b][c]       ← append "c" in place
buffer:  [a][b][c][d]    ← append "d" in place

Same object the whole time. Nothing copied. Nothing thrown away.
```

---

## Useful StringBuilder Methods to Know

```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

sb.append("hello");        // add to the end
sb.insert(0, "say ");      // insert at a position
sb.reverse();              // reverse the contents — useful in interviews
sb.deleteCharAt(2);        // remove a character at index
sb.charAt(0);              // read a character
sb.length();               // current length
sb.toString();             // convert to String when done
```

`sb.reverse()` comes up in palindrome problems — instead of writing your own reverse logic you can do:

```java
String reversed = new StringBuilder(s).reverse().toString();
```

---

## The Interview Explanation

If you write string concatenation in a loop and the interviewer asks about performance, say:

> "String concatenation in a loop is O(n²) in Java because strings are immutable — each `+` creates a new object and copies everything from before. I'd use StringBuilder instead, which appends in place on the same mutable buffer, making the whole loop O(n) with a single `toString()` call at the end."

That answer shows you understand immutability, time complexity, and Java internals — three things in one sentence.

---

## The One Rule

```
Any time you build a string inside a loop → use StringBuilder, never +
Outside a loop, one or two concatenations → + is fine, readable, no issue
```